Hesperis [male] type Colo; 
<typeStatus id="54EE88727B2DFFB2FD47FEF4FCAAD92A" box="[747,852,292,316]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">Neotype</typeStatus>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FCF1FEF3FBC5D92D" authorityName="Edwards" authorityYear="1864" box="[861,1083,291,315]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Argynnis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesperis">Argynnis hesperis</taxonomicName>
[male], 
<collectorName id="26A053067B2DFFB2FB37FEF4FAACD92D" box="[1179,1362,291,315]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">W. H. Edwards</collectorName>
designated by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B2DFFB2FE82FE93FD97D94D" author="dos Passos C. F. &amp; L. P. Grey" box="[302,617,323,347]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" pagination="351 - 360" refId="ref35990" refString="dos Passos C. F., and L. P. Grey. 1965. Notes on certain lectotypes and neotypes designated by the authors in their systematic catalogue of Speyeria (Lepidoptera: Nymphalidae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society 91: 351 - 360." type="journal article" year="1965">dos Passos and Grey 1965</bibRefCitation>
”
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEA36D07B2DFFB2FF6CFE53FAA6DC2D" blockId="31.[192,1441,387,1084]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FF6CFE53FD20D98D" bold="true" box="[192,734,387,411]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">Identification, taxonomy, and variation.</emphasis>
Formerly considered a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FB3AFE54FAEDD98D" box="[1174,1299,387,411]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atlantis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FB3AFE54FAEDD98D" box="[1174,1299,387,411]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. atlantis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FAB3FE54FA5ED98D" authorityName="Edwards" authorityYear="1864" box="[1311,1440,387,411]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Argynnis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesperis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FAB3FE54FA5ED98D" box="[1311,1440,387,411]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. hesperis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is variable throughout its range and 21 subspecific taxa are currently recognized. 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FB35FE74FA92D9AD" box="[1177,1388,419,443]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesperis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FB35FE74FA92D9AD" box="[1177,1388,419,443]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">Speyeria hesperis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FF6CFE14FEBFD9CD" box="[192,321,451,475]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atlantis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FF6CFE14FEBFD9CD" box="[192,321,451,475]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. atlantis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occur together or in close proximity, especially in cool, forested habitats, in many areas of western North America. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B2DFFB2FE5CFE34FCB8D9ED" author="dos Passos C. F. &amp; L. P. Grey" box="[496,838,483,507]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" pagination="351 - 360" refId="ref35990" refString="dos Passos C. F., and L. P. Grey. 1965. Notes on certain lectotypes and neotypes designated by the authors in their systematic catalogue of Speyeria (Lepidoptera: Nymphalidae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society 91: 351 - 360." type="journal article" year="1965">Dos Passos and Grey (1965)</bibRefCitation>
noted that 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FC7EFE34FBA9D9ED" box="[978,1111,483,507]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesperis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FC7EFE34FBA9D9ED" box="[978,1111,483,507]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. hesperis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
represented an unsilvered subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FECBFDD4FE18DA0D" box="[359,486,515,539]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atlantis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FECBFDD4FE18DA0D" box="[359,486,515,539]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. atlantis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
along the Front Range in 
<collectingRegion id="4991F8327B2DFFB2FC8AFDD3FC67DA0D" box="[806,921,515,539]" country="United States of America" name="Colorado" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">Colorado</collectingRegion>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B2DFFB2FC0FFDD3FBAADA0D" author="Tebaldi, A. F." box="[931,1108,515,539]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" refId="ref46585" refString="Tebaldi, A. F. 1982. Genetic and morphological variation in three phenotypes of the Rocky Mountain butterfly Speyeria atlantis. Unpublished Master's Thesis, University of Wyoming; Laramie, Wyoming. 51 p." type="book" year="1982">Tebaldi (1982)</bibRefCitation>
(also see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B2DFFB2FB65FDD3FAA9DA0D" author="Ferris, C. D." box="[1225,1367,515,539]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" pagination="101 - 114" refId="ref38420" refString="Ferris, C. D. 1983. Speyeria atlantis phenotypes in the southern Rocky Mountains (Lepidoptera: Nymphalidae: Argynninae). Journal of Research on the Lepidoptera 22: 101 - 114." type="journal article" year="1983">Ferris 1983</bibRefCitation>
) used starch gel electrophoresis of six enzymes to analyze the relationships among three phenotypes of 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FA8AFDF4FA5EDA2D" box="[1318,1440,547,571]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atlantis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FA8AFDF4FA5EDA2D" box="[1318,1440,547,571]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. atlantis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and found that the phenotypes could be considered “semispecies.” 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B2DFFB2FC49FD93FB47DA4D" author="Scott, J. A. &amp; N. G. Kondla &amp; S. M. Spomer" box="[997,1209,579,603]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" pagination="1 - 31" refId="ref45136" refString="Scott, J. A., N. G. Kondla, and S. M. Spomer. 1998. Speyeria hesperis and Speyeria atlantis are distinct species. Papilio 8: 1 - 31." type="journal article" year="1998">Scott et al. (1998)</bibRefCitation>
divided 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FA8DFD94FA5EDA4D" box="[1313,1440,579,603]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atlantis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FA8DFD94FA5EDA4D" box="[1313,1440,579,603]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. atlantis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
into a distinct species based on wing coloration and wing pattern, 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FC4CFDB3FBBBDA6D" box="[992,1093,611,635]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesperis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FC4CFDB3FBBBDA6D" box="[992,1093,611,635]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">hesperis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
having mostly unsilvered or cream colored ventral hindwing spots and 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FD17FD54FCC6DA8D" box="[699,824,643,667]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atlantis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FD17FD54FD33DA8D" box="[699,717,644,667]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FD76FD53FCC6DA8D" box="[730,824,643,667]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">atlantis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
always silvered. However, this situation still needs to be addressed in greater detail. The original description for 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FC05FD74FBD3DAAD" box="[937,1069,675,699]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesperis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FC05FD74FC45DAAD" box="[937,955,676,699]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FC64FD73FBD3DAAD" box="[968,1069,675,699]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">hesperis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
identifies it as having opaque/ cream colored spots (also see 
<figureCitation id="136E2A557B2DFFB2FD8FFD13FD62DACD" box="[547,668,707,731]" captionStart="Figure 21-25" captionStartId="69.[192,276,1750,1772]" captionTargetBox="[192,1426,198,1725]" captionTargetId="figure-15@69.[192,1426,190,1725]" captionTargetPageId="69" captionText="Figure 21-25. Type images for Speyeria spp.; dorsal, ventral, and label images. 21) Speyeria atlantis canadensis lectotype, described as Argynnis atlantis canadensis, male, AMNH. Now synonymized under Speyeria atlantis (Scott et al. 1998). 22) Speyeria atlantis hollandi holotype, described as Argynnis atlantis Hollandi, male, CNIC. 23) Speyeria atlantis sorocko holotype, described as Speyeria atlantis sorocko, male, AMNH. 24) Speyeria atlantis pahasapa holotype, described as Speyeria atlantis pahasapa, male, AMNH.25) Speyeria hesperis neotype, described as Argynnis Hesperis, male, CMNH. Images 21 and 23-25 by James C. Dunford; 22 by Norbert Kondla." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5352678" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5352678/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">Figure 25</figureCitation>
). Several ‘ 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FCB4FD13FC82DACD" box="[792,892,707,731]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesperis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FCB4FD13FC82DACD" box="[792,892,707,731]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">hesperis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ subspecies (i.e., 
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FBE0FD14FB85DACD" box="[1100,1147,707,731]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. h</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FB25FD13FB30DACD" box="[1161,1230,707,731]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Argynnis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="electa">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FB25FD13FB30DACD" box="[1161,1230,707,731]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">electa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FB70FD14FAF5DACD" box="[1244,1291,707,731]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. h</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FAB5FD14FA67DACD" box="[1305,1433,708,731]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">ratonensis</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FF6CFD34FF0FDAED" box="[192,241,739,763]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. h</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FEACFD33FE74DAED" box="[256,394,739,763]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">schellbachi</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FE35FD34FE37DAED" box="[409,457,739,763]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. h</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FE75FD33FDBBDAED" box="[473,581,739,763]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">dorothea</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FDF8FD34FD7BDAED" box="[596,645,739,763]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. h</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FD38FD34FCFADAED" box="[660,772,740,763]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">nausicaa</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FCBFFD34FCBDDAED" box="[787,835,739,763]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. h</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FCFFFD34FC10DAED" box="[851,1006,740,763]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">capitanensis</emphasis>
) are apparently always silvered. It may be that 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FEFAFCD4FE47DB0D" authorityName="Edwards" authorityYear="1878" box="[342,441,771,795]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="electa">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FEFAFCD4FE47DB0D" box="[342,441,771,795]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. electa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a valid species and represents the silver-spotted western ‘species’ in the atlantis species complex (Cliff Ferris, pers. comm.). Adult wingspan ranges from 
<quantity id="4CAD9B357B2DFFB2FBB5FCF3FB6ADB2D" box="[1049,1172,803,827]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.9" metricValueMax="6.8" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" unit="mm" value="59.0" valueMax="68.0" valueMin="50.0">50-68 mm</quantity>
. The ventral hindwing disc is red-brown to orange-brown and can be silvered or unsilvered. Scott et. al. (1998) split 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FA8DFC94FA5EDB4D" box="[1313,1440,835,859]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atlantis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FA8DFC94FA5EDB4D" box="[1313,1440,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. atlantis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FF58FCB4FE8BDB6D" box="[244,373,867,891]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesperis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FF58FCB4FE8BDB6D" box="[244,373,867,891]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. hesperis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forms based on wing pattern and coloration and a few larval characters. Adult eye coloration in living individuals is blue-gray in some populations, and this may help separate some populations from similar 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FEF2FC74FE0ADBAD" box="[350,500,931,955]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aphrodite">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FEF2FC74FE0ADBAD" box="[350,500,931,955]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. aphrodite</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
populations, which bear dull, yellow-green eyes (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B2DFFB2FBE4FC73FAF7DBAD" author="Glassberg, J." box="[1096,1289,931,955]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" pagination="14 - 17" refId="ref39263" refString="Glassberg, J. 2000. Eyeing the greater fritillaries. American Butterflies 8: 14 - 17." type="journal article" year="2000">Glassberg 2000</bibRefCitation>
). Larvae are generally solid black and bear orange spines with black tips. There are two brown lines located dorsomedially. The pupa is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FD2FFC34FD01DBED" box="[643,767,995,1019]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atlantis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FD2FFC34FD01DBED" box="[643,767,995,1019]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. atlantis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in shape, but stouter; the color is brown on the head and wing cases. The abdomen is brown with some areas yellow-brown. Larval and pupal coloration varies throughout the range of 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FE44FBF4FD95DC2D" box="[488,619,1059,1083]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesperis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FE44FBF4FD95DC2D" box="[488,619,1059,1083]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">S. hesperis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B2DFFB2FD0BFBF3FC94DC2D" author="Scott, J. A. &amp; N. G. Kondla &amp; S. M. Spomer" box="[679,874,1059,1083]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" pagination="1 - 31" refId="ref45136" refString="Scott, J. A., N. G. Kondla, and S. M. Spomer. 1998. Speyeria hesperis and Speyeria atlantis are distinct species. Papilio 8: 1 - 31." type="journal article" year="1998">Scott et al. 1998</bibRefCitation>
) due to various local climatic conditions.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEA36D07B2DFFB2FF6CFBB3FADDDCAD" blockId="31.[192,1441,1123,1211]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FF6CFBB3FEDEDC6D" bold="true" box="[192,288,1123,1147]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">Range.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FE8BFBB4FE00DC6D" box="[295,510,1123,1147]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesperis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FE8BFBB4FE00DC6D" box="[295,510,1123,1147]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">Speyeria hesperis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs from Alaska, central 
<collectingRegion id="4991F8327B2DFFB2FCF3FBB3FC4EDC6D" box="[863,944,1123,1147]" country="Canada" name="Yukon" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">Yukon</collectingRegion>
and southwestern Northwest Territory, south through 
<collectingCountry id="F34276407B2DFFB2FED5FB53FE27DC8D" box="[377,473,1155,1179]" name="Canada" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">Canada</collectingCountry>
east to western 
<collectingRegion id="4991F8327B2DFFB2FD04FB53FCDCDC8D" box="[680,802,1155,1179]" country="Canada" name="Manitoba" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">Manitoba</collectingRegion>
, and in the western 
<collectingCountry id="F34276407B2DFFB2FB8FFB53FB2FDC8D" box="[1059,1233,1155,1179]" name="United States of America" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">United States</collectingCountry>
along the Rocky Mountains, to central 
<collectingRegion id="4991F8327B2DFFB2FE67FB73FDB4DCAD" box="[459,586,1187,1211]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">California</collectingRegion>
, northeastern and central 
<collectingRegion id="4991F8327B2DFFB2FC26FB73FC10DCAD" box="[906,1006,1187,1211]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">Arizona</collectingRegion>
, and central 
<collectingRegion id="4991F8327B2DFFB2FB2BFB74FAE0DCAD" box="[1159,1310,1187,1211]" country="United States of America" name="New Mexico" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">New Mexico</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEA36D07B2DFFB2FF6CFB33FA72DD4D" blockId="31.[192,1440,1251,1372]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FF6CFB33FE95DCED" bold="true" box="[192,363,1251,1275]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">Life history.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B2DFFB2FEDFFB34FDB5DCED" box="[371,587,1251,1275]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hesperis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B2DFFB2FEDFFB34FDB5DCED" box="[371,587,1251,1275]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="30">Speyeria hesperis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forms occur in moist meadows, gulches, and along cool slopes (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B2DFFB2FACCFB33FEF0DD0D" author="Scott, J. A." pageId="31" pageNumber="30" refId="ref44819" refString="Scott, J. A. 1986 b. The butterflies of North America: A natural history and field guide. Stanford University Press; Stanford, California. 583 p." type="book" year="1986">Scott 1986b</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B2DFFB2FEB3FAD3FE40DD0D" author="Scott, J. A." box="[287,446,1283,1307]" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" pagination="1 - 74" refId="ref44961" refString="Scott, J. A. 2006 b. Butterfly hostplant records, 1992 - 2005, with a treatise on the evolution of Erynnis, and a note on new terminology for mate-collecting behavior. Papilio 14: 1 - 74." type="journal article" year="2006">Scott (2006b)</bibRefCitation>
observed females laying eggs on pine needles, 
